value.value: A group of cells that fluoresce for dopamine and are distributed in clusters that, in the primate, are ventral and medial to the mammillothalamic tract of the hypothalamus; a few extend into the reuniens nucleus of the thalamus (Felten-1983). In the mouse A13 is located ventral to the mammillothalamic tract of the thalamus in the zona incerta (adapted from Brain Info).

label.value: nucleus of the brachium of the inferior colliculus

value.value: The line that divided the gluteal regions of the body.
A horizontal crease formed by the inferior aspect of the buttocks and the posterior upper leg.

definition.value: Children with developmental dysplasia of the hips are born with uneven gluteal folds and can be diagnosed with physical examination and sonogram

value.value: A yellowish pungent liquid that is a mixture of the castor sacs (an anal gland in the taxon Castoreum) and urine.
A sweet viscid material elaborated out of the nectar of flowers in the honey sac of various bees.
A bodily fluid consisting of the contents of the digestive tract expulsed through the anterior portion of the digestive tract.
A mass of undigested parts of a bird's food that some bird species occasionally regurgitate from their proventriculus.

definition.value: The contents of a bird's pellet depend on its diet, but can include the exoskeletons of insects, indigestible plant matter, bones, fur, feathers, bills, claws, and teeth

value.value: A non-glandular region of the anal wall in which castoreum is produced.
The endocardial cushion that forms on the ventral surface of the AV canal.
The endocardial cushion that forms on the dorsal surface of the AV canal.
The lower portion of the larynx, extending from just beneath the vocal cords down to the top of the trachea.
One of two longitudinal ridges that develop caudal to the pharynx and fuses to give rise to the tracheoesophageal septum.

The tracheoesophageal septum is formed from the tracheoesophageal folds which fuse in the midline to form a structure called tracheoesophageal septum. It divides the esophagus from the trachea. It divides the foregut tube into the laryngotracheal tube ventrally and esophagus dorsally. Developmental abnormalities can lead to a tracheoesophageal fistula.
A skeletal muscle found in crocodilians that is analogous to the diaphragm of mammals.

A vein that leaves the vestibule through an individual bone canal running parallel to the vestibular aqueduct up to the dura of the posterior side of the petrosa in the area of the endolymphatic sac. It then opens in the inferior petrosal sinus or the jugular bulb. The vein receives other branches from the bone, dura and sac.
The meningeal branch of the mandibular nerve (recurrent branch, nervus spinosus) is a branch of the mandibular nerve that supplies the dura mater.
An infrequent rudimentary duct, or protrusion of the mucous membrane into the incisive canal, on either side of the anterior extremity of the nasal crest.

definition.value: Taxon notes notes: In domestic mammals the Ductus incisivus is considerably better developed than in man. It is not accommodated in a Canalis incisivus, as in man, but in the Fissura palatina[NOMINA ANATOMICA VETERINARIA (2005)]

value.value: Macroscopic waste clearance system that utilizes a unique system of perivascular tunnels, formed by astroglial cells, to promote efficient elimination of soluble proteins and metabolites from the central nervous system.

An region of the mesoderm that includes anterior lateral mesoderm of the first heart field plus contiguous pharyngeal mesoderm that gives rise to second-heart-field-derived regions of the heart and branchiomeric muscles.
A muscle that is part of an oral siphon.
Area of skin in the hypoastric region of the abdomen.
An organ subunit in the skin that gives rise to cutaneous appendage.

A placenta in which the chorionic sac meets the uterine endometrium over its entire surface. The villi of the chorion are distributed evenly throughout the surface of the chorion, and they extend into processes in the uterine endometrium.

A placenta in which the villi clumped together into circular patches called cotyledons. The fetal cotyledon meets with maternal regions called caruncles to form the placentome where maternal-fetal exchanges take place.

A placenta in which the chorionic villi have aggregated to form a broad band that circles about the center of the chorion. Such zones may be complete circles (such as those in dogs and cats) or incomplete (such as those in bears and seals). It is thought that zonary placentae form from diffuse placentae in which the villi at the ends regress, leaving only those in the center to function. At the edges of the zonary placenta is the hemophagous organ, which is green. The color is due to the degradation of hemoglobin into bilivirdin. This green organ provides iron for the developing fetus.

A placenta in which part of the chorion remains smooth, while the other part interacts with the endometrium to form the placenta. The maternal blood cells are in direct contact with the fetal chorion.
A placenta in which all three maternal layers are retained.
A placenta in which the only maternal layer retained is the uterine endothelium.
A placenta in which no maternal layers are retained.
A rostral part of the parahippocampal gyrus.
Sattler's layer is layer of medium diameter blood vessels of the choroid.

definition.value: Some authors consider the vascular region of the choroid as being two separate layers, namely the Sattler's and Haller's layers, and some consider the lamina fusca as being either of scleral or choroidal origin.
